<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
Where a work has two authors always cite both names every time the reference occurs in the text.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Smith and Brown (2056) found that&hellip;
	<br>
	Alternatively: Recent research (Smith &amp; Brown, 2056) supports this view&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
When the author is referred to more than once in the same paragraph do not include the date in 
subsequent references, as long as the work cannot be confused with others cited.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	In a recent study, Smith and Brown (2056) showed that&hellip; Smith and Brown also found 
	that&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
If you are making a direct quotation, use quotation marks and include page numbers.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Smith and Brown (2056) observe that &#34;chocolate has grown in popularity with adolescents&#34; 
	(p. 34).
	<br>
	Alternatively: &#34;Chocolate is growing in popularity with adolescents&#34; (Smith &amp; Brown, 
	2056, p. 34).
</blockquote>
